{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6c8ca6db-d389-4384-8414-e84ffb99ab33","content":"Use preprocessor directives or the `MAUI` platform-specific folders pattern. The cleanest approach in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService>(\n#if ANDROID\n    new AndroidNotificationService()\n#elif IOS\n    new iOSNotificationService()\n#elif WINDOWS\n    new WindowsNotificationService()\n#endif\n);\n```\n\nOr, if you prefer avoiding `#if` in the service registration, use **partial classes** with platform folders:\n\n```\nPlatforms/Android/NotificationService.cs\nPlatforms/iOS/NotificationService.cs\nPlatforms/Windows/NotificationService.cs\n```\n\nEach file defines a `partial class NotificationService : INotificationService` with platform-specific logic. Then register once:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();\n```\n\nThe compiler only includes the file from the target platform's folder automatically (via SDK `.targets` conventions), so it won't break on any platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2c77047c-5589-4ccb-ad66-da29a95357ba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection - specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` interface in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task in the repository.\n\nI'll provide a concise answer showing the standard MAUI pattern for conditional platform registration.","outputTokens":341,"requestId":"081B:37A92F:A87B7F:C322F2:69F2A9EC"},"id":"7c79c487-cd50-4164-83ac-9f7312cc1dcb","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:01:42.005Z","parentId":"d8f00501-5062-418c-9244-a4d31437a12a"}
